.SH "NAME"
pixfade \- darken a pix file
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.sp
\fBpixfade\fP [\-f \fIfraction\fP] [\-p \fIpercentage\fP] [\-m \fImax\fP] [\-s \fIsquaresize\fP] [\-w \fIwidth\fP] [\-n \fIheight\fP] [\-o \fIout_file.pix\fP] [\fIinfile.pix\fP] > \fIoutfile.pix\fP
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.sp
\fBpixfade\fP darkens a color pix file by fading the entire image a
fractional amount or by using a pixel value as a maximum level.
.sp
The \fB\-f\fP option specifies a nonnegative fractional multiplier
which is used to scale the red, green, and blue values of each pixel.
In a similar way, the \fB\-p\fP option is used to specify the
multiplier as a nonnegative percentage. The default is \fB\-f\fP 0.5
(\fB\-p\fP 50.0).
.sp
An alternative way to darken the image is to specify a ceiling pixel
level (0 \- 255) with the \fB\-m\fP option.  The pixel plotted is the
minimum of the ceiling value and each of the red, green, and blue
levels of the pixel.  If this option is used, the \fB\-f\fP and
\fB\-p\fP options are ignored.
.sp
The \fB\-w\fP and \fB\-n\fP flags specify the input file width and
number of scan lines in pixels; they can be set to the same value via
\fB\-s\fP. Default is 512x512.
.sp
The \fB\-o\fP option supplies output file name.  If this option is
omitted, standard output is used.
